<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="39" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,365,711]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,365,391]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Wall asymmetric, comprising four immovable dissimilar calcareous plates: carina, rostrum, scutum and tergum; second scutum and tergum together form a movable operculum; basis membranous or calcareous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="39" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,365,711]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,319,485,511]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39">Remarks.</emphasis>
In addition to the 
<taxonomicName box="[540,670,485,511]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Verrucidae</taxonomicName>
, the Verrucomorpha comprises two other families, the earliest of which, the 
<taxonomicName authority="Newman, 1989 (Newman and Hessler, 1989)" authorityName="Newman, 1989 (Newman and Hessler" authorityYear="1989" box="[283,995,525,551]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Proverrucidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Proverrucidae 
<bibRefCitation author="Newman" box="[456,637,525,551]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" refString="Newman, W. A &amp; Hessler, R. R. (1989) A new abyssal hydrothermal verrucomorphan (Cirripedia; Sessilia): The most primitive living sessile barnacle. Transactions of the San Diego Society of Natural History, 21, 259 - 273." type="journal article" year="1989">
Newman, 
<number box="[578,637,525,551]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" value="1989.0">1989</number>
</bibRefCitation>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Newman" box="[653,986,525,551]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" refString="Newman, W. A &amp; Hessler, R. R. (1989) A new abyssal hydrothermal verrucomorphan (Cirripedia; Sessilia): The most primitive living sessile barnacle. Transactions of the San Diego Society of Natural History, 21, 259 - 273." type="journal article" year="1989">
Newman and Hessler, 
<number box="[924,986,525,551]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" value="1989.0">1989</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, (Cenomanian-Upper Maastrichtian), is characterised by the presence of extra (lateral) plates in the shell wall, and the extant 
<taxonomicName authority="Newman" authorityName="Newman" class="Maxillopoda" family="Neoverrucidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Neoverrucidae Newman</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[210,232,605,630]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="39">in</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Newman" box="[241,550,605,631]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" refString="Newman, W. A &amp; Hessler, R. R. (1989) A new abyssal hydrothermal verrucomorphan (Cirripedia; Sessilia): The most primitive living sessile barnacle. Transactions of the San Diego Society of Natural History, 21, 259 - 273." type="journal article" year="1989">
Newman &amp; Hessler, 
<number box="[489,550,605,631]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" value="1989.0">1989</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, which is a true ‘link’ with early non-verrucomorph barnacles, as it retains several basal whorls of imbricating plates, demonstrating phyletic proximity to a scalpelliform ancestor (
<bibRefCitation author="Newman" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" refString="Newman, W. A. (2000) A new genus and species of barnacle (Cirripedia, Verrucomorpha) associated with vents of the Lau Back-Arc Basin: its gross morphology, inferred first juvenile stage and affinities. Zoosystema, 22, 71 - 84." type="journal article" year="2000">
Newman, 
<number box="[216,278,685,711]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Buckeridge" box="[290,647,685,711]" pageId="2" pageNumber="45" refString="Buckeridge, J. S. &amp; Newman, W. A. (2006) A revision of the Iblidae and the stalked barnacles (Crustacea: Cirripedia: Thoracica), including new ordinal, familial and generic taxa, and two new species from New Zealand and Tasmanian waters. Zootaxa, 1136, 1 - 38." type="journal article" year="2006">
Buckeridge &amp; Newman, 
<number box="[583,647,685,711]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" value="2006.0">2006</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
